      <reaction compartment="compartment_70101" fast="false" id="reaction_9678935" metaid="metaid_103" name="IFNAR2:JAK1:STAT2 binds JAK1,2 inhibitors" reversible="false">
        <notes>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The Janus kinases (JAKs) are a family of intracellular tyrosine kinases that play an essential role in the signaling of numerous cytokines that have been implicated in the pathogenesis of inflammatory diseases. JAK1 binds to and is inhibited by several small molecule drugs (Clark et al. 2014, Fridman et al. 2010). Drugs that inhibit these kinases such as baricitinib, tofacitinib, delgocitinib and ruxolitinib are thus plausible candidates for treatment of severe host inflammatory reactions to viral infection (Peterson et al. 2020, Richardson et al. 2020).</p>
        </notes>
        <annotation>
          <rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:vCard="http://www.w3.org/2001/vcard-rdf/3.0#" xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:bqbiol="http://biomodels.net/biology-qualifiers/">
